===Arcade===
The game was commercially successful in arcades. In Japan, ''Game Machine'' listed ''DragonNinja'' on their May 15, 1988, issue as being the seventh most-successful table arcade unit of the month.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Game Machine's Best Hit Games 25 - テーブル型TVゲーム機 (Table Videos)|magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]]|issue=332|publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press, Inc.]]|date=May 15, 1988|page=21|lang=ja}}</ref> In North America, it was a high-earning arcade game,<ref>{{cite news |title=[[:File:Bad Dudes DragonNinja arcadeflyer.png|How Can Something This Bad Be So Good for Your Earnings? Bad Dudes Vs. Dragon Ninja]] |publisher=[[Data East]] |date=1988}}</ref> becoming one of the top five highest-grossing [[1988 in video games|arcade games of 1988]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=AMOA Awards Nominees |magazine=[[Cash Box]] |date=September 10, 1988 |page=27 |url=https://archive.org/details/cashbox52unse_8/page/27 |publisher=Cash Box Pub. Co.}}</ref> On the UK ''[[Coinslot]]'' charts, during Summer 1988, ''Bad Dudes'' was number two on the monthly arcade video game chart.<ref name="SU77"/> On Hong Kong's annual Bondeal chart, it was the seventh highest-grossing arcade game of 1988.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=April 6, 1989|title=The World's Largest Arcade|url=https://archive.org/details/ACE_Issue_20_1989-05_Future_Publishing_GB/page/n22/mode/1up|magazine=[[ACE (magazine)|ACE]]|issue=20 (May 1989)|page=23}}</ref>

The arcade game received generally positive reviews from critics upon release. ''[[Sinclair User]]'' magazine, in its January 1989 issue, gave it the award for best [[1988 in video games|Beat 'Em Up of 1988]].<ref name="sinclair-award" />

===Home===
In the ZX Spectrum sales charts, it was number two, behind ''[[RoboCop (1988 video game)|Robocop]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ysrnry.co.uk/ys41.htm |title=The YS Rock'n'Roll Years - Issue 41 |publisher=Ysrnry.co.uk |access-date=February 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140126012022/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/ys41.htm |archive-date=January 26, 2014}}</ref>

The home conversions received a generally positive to mixed critical reception. ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' noted the IBM port was satisfactory and compared it favorably to similar ports of ''[[Double Dragon]]'' and ''[[Renegade (video game)|Renegade]]'', but the Apple II port suffered greatly.<ref name="CGW">{{citation | date = May 1989 | last = David M. | first = Russell | magazine = Computer Gaming World | title = Street Lethal | page = 26 | issue=59}}</ref>

President Ronnie, as he appears in the arcade version of the game, was ranked second in ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'''s list of the top ten video game politicians in 2008.<ref>Scott Sharkey, "EGM's Top Ten Videogame Politicians: Election time puts us in a voting mood", ''Electronic Gaming Monthly'' 234 (November 2008): 97.</ref> In 2010, [[UGO]] wrote: "No ninja game retrospective could possibly be complete without some mention of ... ''Bad Dudes''".<ref>[http://www.ugo.com/games/ninjas-in-games-top-11-bad-dudes Ninjas in Games | An evolution of ninjas in video games throughout the years.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615194013/http://www.ugo.com/games/ninjas-in-games-top-11-bad-dudes |date=June 15, 2011}}, UGO.com, June 4, 2008.</ref> In 2013, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' had it top their list of "the video games where you kick ass in the name of America" as the most American game of them all.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/video-games/2013/07/25-best-video-games-where-you-kick-ass-name-america/bad |title=Bad Dudes vs. Dragon Ninja — The 25 Best Video Games Where You Kick Ass in the Name of America |publisher=Complex |access-date=February 10, 2014}}</ref>

==Legacy==
The game was followed by a [[1991 in video gaming|1991]] spiritual successor ''[[Two Crude]]'' (known in Japan as ''Crude Buster''). A sequel attempt, supposed to take place 23 years after the first game, was unsuccessfully attempted to be financed via [[Kickstarter]] by Pinstripe Games in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/pinstripegames/bad-dudes-2 |title=Bad Dudes 2 by Pinstripe Games — Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter.com |date=December 1, 2012 |access-date=February 10, 2014}}</ref>

The arcade version of the game appears in the 1989 film ''[[Parenthood (1989 film)|Parenthood]]'', in which the son of [[Steve Martin]]'s character wonders why the game is so difficult. Martin, grasping for an answer, says, "Well, they're bad dudes. That's why they call the game ''Bad Dudes''". The ''Bad Dudes'' logo can be seen at the end of Stage 4 in ''[[Sly Spy]]'', another Data East arcade game. In the 1990 film ''[[RoboCop 2]]'', Officer Duffy gets pushed by RoboCop into a ''Bad Dudes Vs. DragonNinja'' arcade cabinet, but with ''Sly Spy'' built into it.<ref>{{cite web | title=ROBOCOP 2 - TRIVIA | work=RoboCop Archive | url=http://www.robocoparchive.com/info/making2-2.htm | access-date=September 7, 2008}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Along with a few other Data East arcade games, they appeared in the film due to licensing and advertising agreements between [[Orion Pictures]], Data East and Ocean Software after the release of two video games based on the ''[[RoboCop]]'' property.|group="note"}}

The game's introduction, challenging the player to be a "bad enough dude to rescue the President", became a popular [[Internet meme]] and is often lampooned on various websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.somethingawful.com/d/news/philosophy-sunday-dudes.php |title=Philosophy Sunday: Dudes. Are they bad enough? |publisher=Somethingawful.com |date=February 5, 2006 |access-date=February 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5352011/are-you-a-bad-enough-dude-for-this-data-east-collection |title=Are You A Bad Enough Dude For This Data East Collection? |date=September 3, 2009 |publisher=Kotaku.com |access-date=February 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/03/10-1/are-you-a-bad-enough-dude-to-build-this-plastic-pot-sticker-model |title=Are You a Bad Enough Dude to Build This Plastic Pot Sticker Model? |publisher=Crunchyroll.com |date=March 10, 2012 |access-date=February 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/tell-me-are-you-a-bad-enough-dude-to-chicky-chicky-down--150547.phtml |title=Tell me: Are you a bad enough dude to chicky chicky down? |date=October 2009 |publisher=Destructoid.com |access-date=February 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kuchera |first=Ben |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/news/2005/12/2155.ars |title=Are you a bad enough dude to blow up a giant woman? |publisher=Arstechnica.com |date=December 20, 2005 |access-date=February 19, 2014}}</ref> The 2008 video game ''[[Sam & Max Beyond Time and Space]]'' spoofs on the ''Bad Dudes'' intro in the episode "[[Chariots of the Dogs]]". Alternative rock band [[Lostprophets]]' first release, ''[[The Fake Sound of Progress]]'', includes a track titled "[[Shinobi vs. Dragon Ninja]]" in a reference to the video games ''[[Shinobi (series)|Shinobi]]'' and ''Bad Dudes vs. DragonNinja''. The webcomic ''[[The Adventures of Dr. McNinja]]'' often references the Bad Dudes, among many other 1980s pop culture touchstones.

An updated version of the game has been announced for release exclusively for the [[Intellivision Amico]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Intellivision® Reveals Initial Details For The Upcoming Amico™ Home Video Game Console!|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/intellivision-reveals-initial-details-for-the-upcoming-amico-home-video-game-console-300734998.html|website=PR Newswire}}</ref>

