==Rereleases==
Reissues of the game were nonexistent in the two decades that followed its original release. In recent years, however, rereleases of the original arcade version ''Bad Dudes Vs. DragonNinja'' and its NES port ''Bad Dudes'' have become increasingly common:
* ''Bad Dudes Vs. DragonNinja'' is one of the 15 arcade games included in [[Data East Arcade Classics]] released in February 2010 for the [[Wii]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendolife.com/games/wii/data_east_arcade_classics|title=Data East Arcade Classics|first=Nintendo|last=Life|date=March 1, 2010|website=Nintendo Life}}</ref>
* The arcade version is on the [[Zeebo]] Brazilian home console released in 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pvNx6SFl9bA | title=Bad Dudes - Zeebo (Trailer Site Oficial) | website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>  
* The NES version is included in the compilation ''Retro-Bit Data East All Star Collection'', a multi-cart of five Data East games released in 2017 for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2017/10/retro-bit_lifts_the_lid_on_its_multi-cart_collections_for_the_nes_and_snes|title=Retro-Bit Lifts The Lid On Its Multi-Cart Collections For The NES And SNES|date=27 October 2017|website=Nintendo Life}}</ref> Another compilation from the same manufacturer called ''8 Bit Collection Data East Vol.01'', with a similar assortment of titles, was released the following year in Japan for the Retro Duo [[famiclone]] and includes the American NES port of ''Bad Dudes'' unlike the rest of the Data East games of that regional collection that are all in their Famicom versions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/383/G038375/20180202066/|title=レトロビット「レトロデュオ」に向けて，ジャレコとデータイースト，アテナの名作をそれぞれまとめたカートリッジが2月28日に発売|website=[[4Gamer.net]]}}</ref>  
* The game is part of the [[dedicated console]] ''Super Retro-Cade'' released in late 2017 and is one of the few titles in the compilation to have both its arcade and NES versions included.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/361545-retro-bit-super-retro-cade-review-high-quality-retropie-killer|title=Retro-Bit Super Retro-Cade Review - A High-Quality RetroPie Killer|date=December 31, 2017}}</ref>
* The arcade version was released in 2018 for the [[Nintendo Switch]] as part of [[Flying Tiger Development|Flying Tiger]]'s Johnny Turbo series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/switch-eshop/johnny_turbos_arcade_bad_dudes|title=Review: Johnny Turbo's Arcade: Bad Dudes (Switch eShop)|first=Nintendo|last=Life|date=March 19, 2018|website=Nintendo Life}}</ref>
* Since 2018, the retro gaming company My Arcade has released the NES version on different occasions either as a standalone mini-arcade cabinet <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.myarcadegaming.com/collections/retro-gaming/products/bad-dudes-micro-arcade |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 29, 2020 |archive-date=October 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201029112141/https://www.myarcadegaming.com/collections/retro-gaming/products/bad-dudes-micro-arcade |url-status=live }}</ref> or as part of a collection of 8 Data East games, both as a mini-cabinet<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myarcadegaming.com/products/data-east-hits-micro-player-1|title=Data East Hits Micro Player|website=My Arcade®}}</ref> and handheld console.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myarcadegaming.com/products/data-east-hits-pocket-player-1|title=Data East Hits Pocket Player|website=My Arcade®}}</ref> The same company had also released the arcade version ''Bad Dudes Vs. DragonNinja'' in a compilation that included more than 30 Data East games in the form of a mini-arcade cabinet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myarcadegaming.com/products/data-east-mini-player|title=Data East™ Mini Player™ Arcade from My Arcade®|date=February 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201100654/https://myarcadegaming.com/products/data-east-mini-player |archive-date=February 1, 2019}}</ref>
* In early 2020, ''Bad Dudes Vs. DragonNinja'' along with three other Data East classics were released in an actual [[arcade cabinet]] at the cost of 399$ by manufacturer [[Arcade1Up]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/new-burger-time-arcade-cabinet-nba-jam-with-online/1100-6472495/|title=New Burger Time Arcade Cabinet, NBA Jam With Online Multiplayer Revealed By Arcade1Up}}</ref>
* The arcade version and the NES port are each included in their respective collections for the [[Evercade]] handheld console.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/evercade-vs-review|title=Evercade VS Review|first=Matthew|last=Adler|date=November 5, 2021|website=IGN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://evercade.net/home/cartridge-03/|title=Cartridge 03 – Data East Collection – Evercade Network}}</ref>

